    "rationale": "MOA DETAIL: Gabapentin and pregabalin bind the ALPHA-2-DELTA (α2δ) SUBUNIT of presynaptic voltage-gated calcium channels (specifically α2δ-1). This binding REDUCES calcium influx at hyperexcitable presynaptic nerve terminals, thereby DECREASING the release of excitatory neurotransmitters (glutamate, norepinephrine, substance P) from dorsal root ganglion neurons and spinal dorsal horn. This attenuates the pathological wind-up and central sensitization that drives neuropathic pain. Despite the name 'gabapentin,' these drugs do NOT directly bind GABA receptors or affect GABA metabolism.\n\nKEY MEDICATIONS: gabapentin, pregabalin\n\nCLINICAL APPLICATION: Within Neuro (PNS/CNS), this scenario is best explained by presynaptic calcium-channel subunit modulation to reduce excitatory release.",
    "explanationA": "COX-1 inhibition (NSAIDs) reduces prostaglandin-mediated inflammatory pain but is ineffective for neuropathic pain, which involves aberrant neuronal firing rather than prostaglandin-driven inflammation.",
    "explanationB": "Correct. α2δ calcium channel subunit binding reduces presynaptic calcium entry → decreased excitatory neurotransmitter release → attenuated neuropathic pain signaling. This is distinct from voltage-gated sodium channel blockade (AEDs) or opioid receptor agonism.",
    "explanationC": "IL-5 neutralization targets eosinophilic inflammation — irrelevant to the calcium channel-mediated excitatory neurotransmitter release that drives neuropathic pain.",
    "explanationD": "DNA gyrase inhibition is an antibacterial mechanism with no analgesic properties. Fluoroquinolones can actually CAUSE neuropathy as an adverse effect.",
    "examTip": "Gabapentin/pregabalin: FDA-approved for postherpetic neuralgia, diabetic neuropathy (pregabalin), fibromyalgia (pregabalin). Renal elimination — dose-adjust for eGFR. Pregabalin is Schedule V (abuse potential, euphoria). Common side effects: sedation, dizziness, peripheral edema, weight gain. NOT effective for acute/nociceptive pain.",
