    "optionA": "Irreversible COX-1 inhibition as a universal first-line strategy",
    "optionB": "enhancement of synaptic acetylcholine through enzyme inhibition",
    "optionC": "Skeletal neuromuscular nicotinic agonism as the core therapeutic pathway",
    "optionD": "Direct bacterial DNA gyrase inhibition independent of disease context",
    "correctAnswer": "B",
    "rationale": "MOA DETAIL: Alzheimer's disease involves degeneration of cholinergic neurons in the nucleus basalis of Meynert, reducing cortical acetylcholine (ACh). CHOLINESTERASE INHIBITORS (donepezil, rivastigmine, galantamine) reversibly inhibit acetylcholinesterase (AChE) enzyme, preventing ACh breakdown and increasing synaptic ACh concentration. Donepezil is selective for AChE; rivastigmine inhibits both AChE and butyrylcholinesterase (BuChE). Galantamine also allosterically modulates nicotinic ACh receptors. MEMANTINE (NMDA antagonist) is added in moderate-severe AD to reduce glutamate excitotoxicity.\n\nKEY MEDICATIONS: donepezil, rivastigmine, galantamine, memantine\n\nCLINICAL APPLICATION: Within Neuro (PNS/CNS), this scenario is best explained by enhancement of synaptic acetylcholine through enzyme inhibition.",
