    "stem": "A 12-year-old boy with absence epilepsy has convulsive seizures for the first time. His provider adds a sodium channel-blocking AED to his ethosuximide. Which mechanism explains the broad-spectrum seizure control of this drug class?",
    "optionA": "Skeletal neuromuscular nicotinic agonism as the core therapeutic pathway",
    "optionB": "use-dependent sodium-channel suppression of pathologic firing",
    "optionC": "Direct bacterial DNA gyrase inhibition independent of disease context",
    "optionD": "Exclusive IL-5 neutralization in eosinophilic pathways as the primary mechanism",
    "correctAnswer": "B",
    "rationale": "MOA DETAIL: Antiepileptic drugs (AEDs) such as phenytoin, carbamazepine, and lamotrigine exert their effects through USE-DEPENDENT BLOCKADE of voltage-gated sodium channels. These drugs preferentially bind to the INACTIVATED state of the Nav1.1–Nav1.6 channels, stabilizing them and preventing the rapid, repetitive neuronal firing that underlies seizure propagation. Lacosamide uniquely enhances SLOW inactivation rather than fast inactivation. This use-dependent property means normal neuronal firing is minimally affected while pathologically rapid firing is suppressed.\n\nKEY MEDICATIONS: carbamazepine, phenytoin, lamotrigine, oxcarbazepine, lacosamide\n\nCLINICAL APPLICATION: Within Neuro (PNS/CNS), this scenario is best explained by use-dependent sodium-channel suppression of pathologic firing.",
    "explanationA": "COX-1 inhibition (aspirin, NSAIDs) affects prostaglandin synthesis for inflammation/platelet aggregation — has no anticonvulsant mechanism and does not modulate ion channels involved in seizure propagation.",
    "explanationB": "Correct. Use-dependent sodium channel blockade preferentially suppresses rapid pathological firing (seizure foci) while sparing normal neuronal activity. Phenytoin binds the inactivated state of Nav channels, prolonging the refractory period. Lamotrigine also inhibits glutamate release. Carbamazepine has additional effects on calcium channels.",
    "explanationC": "DNA gyrase inhibition describes fluoroquinolone antibiotics (ciprofloxacin, levofloxacin) — a bactericidal mechanism entirely unrelated to neuronal sodium channel pharmacology.",
    "explanationD": "Nicotinic receptor agonism at the neuromuscular junction (e.g., succinylcholine) causes depolarization and paralysis — opposite of the selective neuronal sodium channel stabilization used in seizure control.",
    "examTip": "Sodium channel AEDs: phenytoin (zero-order kinetics!), carbamazepine (CYP3A4 auto-inducer), lamotrigine (requires slow titration for Stevens-Johnson syndrome prevention; dose halved with valproate co-administration), oxcarbazepine (hyponatremia risk), lacosamide (PR prolongation). All share the use-dependent binding principle but differ in pharmacokinetics and side effects.",
