    "explanationB": "Correct. Sumatriptan's 5-HT1B/1D agonism provides migraine-specific relief through cranial vasoconstriction (1B) and trigeminal neuropeptide release inhibition (1D). This explains both efficacy and cardiovascular contraindications — vasoconstriction is therapeutic in cranial but dangerous in coronary vessels.",
    "explanationC": "IL-5 neutralization (mepolizumab) targets eosinophilic inflammation in severe asthma — a fundamentally different pathway from the serotonergic trigeminovascular circuit targeted by triptans.",
    "explanationD": "COX-1 inhibition describes NSAIDs/aspirin which provide nonspecific anti-inflammatory analgesia — unlike triptans which specifically target the 5-HT1B/1D receptors mediating migraine pathophysiology.",
    "examTip": "Triptans CONTRAINDICATED in: coronary artery disease, Prinzmetal angina, uncontrolled HTN, hemiplegic/basilar migraine, concurrent MAOIs, within 24h of ergotamine. Newer alternative: CGRP monoclonal antibodies (erenumab, fremanezumab, galcanezumab) for migraine PREVENTION — block CGRP directly without vasoconstriction risk.",
