    "correctAnswer": "B",
    "rationale": "MOA DETAIL: Dopaminergic therapy in Parkinson's disease targets the nigrostriatal pathway where dopaminergic neurons degenerate. LEVODOPA (L-DOPA) is the direct precursor to dopamine — it crosses the blood-brain barrier (unlike dopamine itself), where it is converted to dopamine by DOPA decarboxylase. CARBIDOPA inhibits peripheral DOPA decarboxylase, preventing levodopa's peripheral conversion (reducing nausea, increasing CNS availability). DOPAMINE AGONISTS (pramipexole, ropinirole) directly stimulate D2/D3 receptors. COMT INHIBITORS (entacapone) block peripheral levodopa degradation. MAO-B INHIBITORS (selegiline, rasagiline) prevent central dopamine breakdown.\n\nKEY MEDICATIONS: carbidopa-levodopa, pramipexole, ropinirole, entacapone, selegiline, amantadine\n\nCLINICAL APPLICATION: Within Neuro (PNS/CNS), this scenario is best explained by targeted modulation of dopamine signaling across motor/limbic tracts.",
    "explanationA": "COX-1 inhibition has no role in dopaminergic signaling or Parkinson's treatment. Prostaglandin pathways do not modulate the basal ganglia motor circuits affected in PD.",
    "explanationB": "Correct. Targeted modulation of dopaminergic signaling across motor and limbic tracts is the cornerstone of Parkinson's therapy. The nigrostriatal pathway (motor) and mesolimbic pathway (mood/motivation) both rely on adequate dopamine — explaining both motor symptoms and the neuropsychiatric features of PD.",
    "explanationC": "Nicotinic agonism at the NMJ causes muscle contraction — a peripheral mechanism unrelated to the central dopaminergic deficiency that underlies parkinsonian motor symptoms.",
    "explanationD": "DNA gyrase inhibition targets bacterial topoisomerase — an antimicrobial mechanism with no relevance to central dopaminergic neurotransmission.",
