    "stem": "A 23-year-old man with juvenile myoclonic epilepsy on oxcarbazepine reports worsening myoclonic jerks but improved focal seizures. What is the sodium channel mechanism that helps focal but may worsen generalized seizures?",
    "optionA": "Skeletal neuromuscular nicotinic agonism as the core therapeutic pathway",
    "optionB": "use-dependent sodium-channel suppression of pathologic firing",
    "optionC": "Irreversible COX-1 inhibition as a universal first-line strategy",
    "optionD": "Exclusive IL-5 neutralization in eosinophilic pathways as the primary mechanism",
    "correctAnswer": "B",
    "rationale": "MOA DETAIL: Antiepileptic drugs (AEDs) such as phenytoin, carbamazepine, and lamotrigine exert their effects through USE-DEPENDENT BLOCKADE of voltage-gated sodium channels. These drugs preferentially bind to the INACTIVATED state of the Nav1.1–Nav1.6 channels, stabilizing them and preventing the rapid, repetitive neuronal firing that underlies seizure propagation. Lacosamide uniquely enhances SLOW inactivation rather than fast inactivation. This use-dependent property means normal neuronal firing is minimally affected while pathologically rapid firing is suppressed.\n\nKEY MEDICATIONS: carbamazepine, phenytoin, lamotrigine, oxcarbazepine, lacosamide\n\nCLINICAL APPLICATION: Within Neuro (PNS/CNS), this scenario is best explained by use-dependent sodium-channel suppression of pathologic firing.",
