    "rationale": "MOA DETAIL: Antihypertensives modulate vascular tone through distinct mechanisms: (1) CALCIUM CHANNEL BLOCKERS (amlodipine, nifedipine) — block L-type Ca2+ channels in vascular smooth muscle → reduced calcium entry → vasodilation → decreased SVR. (2) ACE INHIBITORS (lisinopril, enalapril) — block ACE converting angiotensin I to angiotensin II → reduced vasoconstriction + reduced aldosterone → decreased preload and afterload. (3) ARBs (losartan, valsartan) — directly block AT1 receptors. (4) DIRECT VASODILATORS (hydralazine) — open K+ channels in arteriolar smooth muscle. (5) Alpha-1 blockers (doxazosin) — block α1-adrenergic vasoconstriction. (6) Central α2 agonists (clonidine) — reduce central sympathetic outflow.\n\nKEY MEDICATIONS: amlodipine, nifedipine, lisinopril, losartan, hydralazine, doxazosin, clonidine\n\nCLINICAL APPLICATION: Within Cardiovascular, this scenario is best explained by receptor-mediated reduction in maladaptive sympathetic drive.",
