    "rationale": "MOA DETAIL: STATINS (atorvastatin, rosuvastatin) inhibit HMG-CoA reductase — the rate-limiting enzyme in hepatic cholesterol synthesis (mevalonate pathway). Reduced intracellular cholesterol → upregulation of hepatic LDL receptors → increased LDL clearance from blood. Beyond lipid lowering, statins have PLEIOTROPIC effects: anti-inflammatory (reduced CRP), endothelial function improvement, plaque stabilization. EZETIMIBE blocks NPC1L1 (Niemann-Pick C1-Like 1) transporter in intestinal enterocytes, reducing dietary cholesterol absorption. PCSK9 INHIBITORS (monoclonal antibodies) prevent PCSK9-mediated degradation of hepatic LDL receptors → more LDL receptors on hepatocyte surface → markedly increased LDL clearance.\n\nKEY MEDICATIONS: atorvastatin, rosuvastatin, ezetimibe, PCSK9 inhibitors (evolocumab, alirocumab), icosapent ethyl\n\nCLINICAL APPLICATION: Within Cardiovascular, this scenario is best explained by hepatic LDL-clearance enhancement via synthesis/uptake pathways.",
