    "rationale": "MOA DETAIL: Anti-anginal therapy reduces myocardial oxygen demand or increases supply: (1) NITRATES (nitroglycerin, isosorbide mononitrate) → converted to nitric oxide (NO) → activates guanylyl cyclase → increases cGMP → venodilation (primary: reduces PRELOAD) + arteriolar dilation (reduces AFTERLOAD). (2) BETA-BLOCKERS (metoprolol) → reduce heart rate, contractility, and BP → decreased myocardial O2 demand. (3) CCBs (amlodipine) → arteriolar vasodilation → reduced afterload; verapamil/diltiazem also reduce HR. (4) RANOLAZINE → inhibits late sodium current (INa-late), reducing intracellular Ca2+ overload and diastolic tension without affecting heart rate or BP.\n\nKEY MEDICATIONS: nitroglycerin, isosorbide mononitrate, amlodipine, metoprolol, ranolazine\n\nCLINICAL APPLICATION: Within Cardiovascular, this scenario is best explained by preload/afterload optimization through vasoactive signaling.",
