    "rationale": "MOA DETAIL: Heart failure with reduced ejection fraction (HFrEF) is driven by maladaptive neurohormonal activation: RAAS and sympathetic nervous system. GUIDELINE-DIRECTED MEDICAL THERAPY (GDMT) targets these pathways: (1) ACEi/ARB or ARNI — block angiotensin II-mediated vasoconstriction, aldosterone release, and cardiac remodeling. ARNI (sacubitril/valsartan) adds neprilysin inhibition enhancing natriuretic peptides. (2) Beta-blockers (carvedilol, metoprolol succinate, bisoprolol) — block β1-mediated tachycardia and myocyte toxicity. (3) MRAs (spironolactone, eplerenone) — block aldosterone-mediated fibrosis and potassium wasting. (4) SGLT2i — cardiometabolic benefits independent of glucose. These four pillars reduce mortality additively.\n\nKEY MEDICATIONS: sacubitril/valsartan (ARNI), carvedilol, metoprolol succinate, spironolactone, eplerenone, enalapril, lisinopril\n\nCLINICAL APPLICATION: Within Cardiovascular, this scenario is best explained by RAAS signal interruption reducing remodeling and afterload stress.",
