    "rationale": "MOA DETAIL: Antiarrhythmic drugs are classified by the Vaughan-Williams system based on their ion channel targets: CLASS I (Na+ channel blockers): IA (procainamide — moderate block, prolongs AP), IB (lidocaine — weak block, shortens AP), IC (flecainide — strong block, no AP change). CLASS II (beta-blockers): metoprolol — blocks β1-adrenergic stimulation of SA/AV node, reducing automaticity and conduction velocity. CLASS III (K+ channel blockers): amiodarone — blocks IKr, IKs, prolonging repolarization (QT prolongation), also has Class I/II/IV properties. CLASS IV (Ca2+ channel blockers): diltiazem, verapamil — block L-type Ca2+ channels in SA/AV node, slowing conduction. ADENOSINE: activates A1 receptors → opens K+ channels → hyperpolarizes AV node → transient AV block.\n\nKEY MEDICATIONS: metoprolol, diltiazem, verapamil, amiodarone, flecainide, digoxin, adenosine\n\nCLINICAL APPLICATION: Within Cardiovascular, this scenario is best explained by nodal ion-channel and receptor-level conduction slowing.",
