    "explanationB": "Correct. Understanding whether a drug is anti-resorptive (slows bone loss) or anabolic (builds new bone) is essential. Bisphosphonates and denosumab target osteoclasts; teriparatide and romosozumab stimulate osteoblasts — fundamentally different approaches to the same disease.",
    "explanationC": "DNA gyrase inhibition has no role in bone metabolism.",
    "explanationD": "NMJ nicotinic agonism affects skeletal muscle, not bone remodeling cells.",
    "examTip": "Bisphosphonate administration: empty stomach, upright 30-60 min, with plain water only (prevents esophageal ulceration). Denosumab: rebound vertebral fractures if discontinued. Teriparatide: 2-year max (osteosarcoma risk in rats). Romosozumab: CV risk warning. Sequence therapy: anabolic first → then anti-resorptive for best outcomes.",
