    "rationale": "MOA DETAIL: The INCRETIN AXIS: GLP-1 (glucagon-like peptide-1) and GIP (glucose-dependent insulinotropic peptide) are gut hormones released after eating. GLP-1 RECEPTOR AGONISTS (semaglutide, liraglutide) mimic GLP-1 with enhanced half-life. Effects: (1) GLUCOSE-DEPENDENT insulin secretion (low hypoglycemia risk), (2) glucagon suppression, (3) delayed gastric emptying, (4) central appetite suppression → weight loss 10-15%, (5) cardiovascular protection (SUSTAIN-6, SELECT). DPP-4 INHIBITORS (sitagliptin) prevent GLP-1 degradation — less potent than exogenous GLP-1 RAs. Never combine GLP-1 RA + DPP-4 inhibitor (redundant).\n\nKEY MEDICATIONS: semaglutide, liraglutide, dulaglutide, exenatide, sitagliptin, saxagliptin\n\nCLINICAL APPLICATION: Within Endocrine, this scenario is best explained by glucose-dependent insulin support with counter-regulatory suppression.",
    "explanationA": "COX inhibition is unrelated to glucose homeostasis or incretin signaling.",
    "explanationB": "Correct. GLP-1 receptor agonism provides glucose-dependent insulin secretion (unlike sulfonylureas), weight loss, and CV benefit — making it preferred over older agents. The incretin pathway harnesses the gut-pancreas hormonal axis for multi-organ benefit.",
    "explanationC": "DNA gyrase inhibition has no metabolic application.",
    "explanationD": "NMJ nicotinic agonism does not modulate insulin secretion or glucose metabolism.",
    "examTip": "GLP-1 RA Black Box: thyroid C-cell tumors in rats → contraindicated in personal/family history of medullary thyroid carcinoma (MTC) or MEN2. Side effects: nausea (most common, dose-related), pancreatitis risk. Hierarchy for weight loss: semaglutide > liraglutide > dulaglutide. NEW: tirzepatide (dual GIP/GLP-1 agonist) — even greater weight loss and glucose reduction.",
