    "explanationB": "Correct. The dual strategy of acidifying the colon (lactulose trapping NH3 as NH4+) and reducing ammonia-producing bacteria (rifaximin) addresses HE pathophysiology at both the chemical and microbial level.",
    "explanationC": "DNA gyrase inhibition targets Gram-negative bacteria systemically; rifaximin works locally in the gut without systemic absorption — an important distinction.",
    "explanationD": "NMJ agonism has no role in hepatic ammonia management.",
    "examTip": "Lactulose dosing: titrate to 2-3 soft bowel movements per day. Excessive dosing → dehydration, hypernatremia, hypokalemia. Rifaximin: well-tolerated, minimal resistance development due to non-systemic mechanism. HE triggers to identify: GI bleeding, infection, constipation, dehydration, excessive protein intake, medication non-adherence.",
