    "optionA": "Exclusive IL-5 neutralization in eosinophilic pathways as the primary mechanism",
    "optionB": "targeted cytokine network inhibition in synovial tissues",
    "optionC": "Skeletal neuromuscular nicotinic agonism as the core therapeutic pathway",
    "optionD": "Direct bacterial DNA gyrase inhibition independent of disease context",
    "correctAnswer": "B",
    "rationale": "MOA DETAIL: RHEUMATOID ARTHRITIS therapy follows a treat-to-target strategy: (1) csDMARDs: METHOTREXATE (anchor drug) — DHFR inhibition + adenosine-mediated anti-inflammation. HYDROXYCHLOROQUINE — accumulates in lysosomes → raises pH → inhibits antigen processing and TLR signaling. LEFLUNOMIDE — inhibits dihydroorotate dehydrogenase (DHODH) → blocks de novo pyrimidine synthesis → suppresses proliferating lymphocytes. (2) bDMARDs: TNF INHIBITORS (adalimumab, etanercept) — neutralize TNFα, the key pro-inflammatory cytokine driving synovial inflammation and joint destruction. (3) tsDMARDs: JAK INHIBITORS (tofacitinib) — block JAK1/JAK3 → inhibit cytokine signaling (IL-6, interferons, IL-2) at the intracellular level.\n\nKEY MEDICATIONS: methotrexate, hydroxychloroquine, sulfasalazine, leflunomide, adalimumab, etanercept, tofacitinib\n\nCLINICAL APPLICATION: Within Musculoskeletal, this scenario is best explained by targeted cytokine network inhibition in synovial tissues.",
    "explanationA": "COX inhibition (NSAIDs) provides symptomatic relief but does NOT modify disease progression or prevent joint destruction.",
    "explanationB": "Correct. RA treatment targets multiple levels of the autoimmune inflammatory cascade: innate immune processing (HCQ), lymphocyte proliferation (MTX, leflunomide), extracellular cytokines (anti-TNF), and intracellular signaling (JAK inhibitors). Methotrexate remains first-line based on decades of efficacy evidence.",
    "explanationC": "DNA gyrase inhibition is irrelevant to autoimmune pathology.",
    "explanationD": "NMJ agonism has no role in synovial inflammation.",
    "examTip": "Start methotrexate early in RA diagnosis — delay causes irreversible joint damage. Anti-TNF: infection screening (TB, Hep B) required before initiation. JAK inhibitors: BLACK BOX for serious infections, malignancy, thromboembolism, cardiovascular events. Leflunomide: teratogenic (long washout — requires cholestyramine for elimination if pregnancy planned).",
    "category": "Physical Assessment",
    "subtopic": "Musculoskeletal - autoimmune synovial inflammation control",
