    "correctAnswer": "B",
    "rationale": "MOA DETAIL: URATE-LOWERING THERAPY targets uric acid metabolism: (1) XANTHINE OXIDASE INHIBITORS (allopurinol, febuxostat) — block the enzyme converting hypoxanthine → xanthine → uric acid, REDUCING PRODUCTION. Allopurinol is a purine analog (structural mimicry); febuxostat is a non-purine selective inhibitor. (2) URICOSURICS (probenecid) — block URAT1 transporter in the proximal tubule → reduce uric acid reabsorption → increased urinary excretion. (3) PEGLOTICASE — recombinant pegylated uricase → converts uric acid to allantoin (highly soluble) → very effective but immunogenicity and infusion reactions limit use to refractory gout.\n\nKEY MEDICATIONS: allopurinol, febuxostat, probenecid, pegloticase\n\nCLINICAL APPLICATION: Within Musculoskeletal, this scenario is best explained by enzyme-level uric acid production reduction.",
