    "stem": "A 55-year-old man with euvolemic hyponatremia from SIADH takes oral tolvaptan. His sodium corrects 8 mEq/L in 24 hours. His provider closely monitors correction rate. What is the mechanism of osmotic demyelination syndrome from overly rapid sodium correction?",
    "optionA": "Skeletal neuromuscular nicotinic agonism as the core therapeutic pathway",
    "optionB": "collecting-duct receptor activation for antidiuretic response",
    "optionC": "Direct bacterial DNA gyrase inhibition independent of disease context",
    "optionD": "Irreversible COX-1 inhibition as a universal first-line strategy",
    "correctAnswer": "B",
    "rationale": "MOA DETAIL: VASOPRESSIN (ADH) SYSTEM regulation: (1) DESMOPRESSIN (DDAVP) — synthetic ADH analog selective for V2 receptors in collecting duct → stimulates aquaporin-2 (AQP2) insertion into apical membrane → water reabsorption → concentrated urine. Used in: central diabetes insipidus, nocturnal enuresis, hemophilia A/vWD (releases vWF from endothelial stores via V2). (2) VAPTANS (tolvaptan, conivaptan) — vasopressin receptor ANTAGONISTS → block V2 (tolvaptan is V2-selective; conivaptan blocks V1a + V2) → prevent AQP2 insertion → water diuresis without sodium loss (aquaresis). Used in: SIADH, hyponatremia, autosomal dominant polycystic kidney disease (tolvaptan slows cyst growth).\n\nKEY MEDICATIONS: desmopressin, tolvaptan, conivaptan\n\nCLINICAL APPLICATION: Within Urinary, this scenario is best explained by collecting-duct receptor activation for antidiuretic response.",
    "explanationA": "COX inhibition does not directly modulate the vasopressin-aquaporin axis.",
    "explanationB": "Correct. Water balance pharmacotherapy directly targets the vasopressin axis: DDAVP activates V2 receptors (enhancing water reabsorption for DI), while vaptans block V2 receptors (promoting free water excretion for SIADH/hyponatremia). Understanding V2→AQP2 signaling is key to both.",
    "explanationC": "DNA gyrase inhibition has no role in water balance regulation.",
    "explanationD": "NMJ agonism is irrelevant to renal collecting duct physiology.",
    "examTip": "Tolvaptan: Na+ correction must not exceed 10-12 mEq/L/24h (risk of osmotic demyelination syndrome/central pontine myelinolysis). Hepatotoxicity risk — monitor LFTs. Desmopressin: hyponatremia risk (water retention) — monitor Na+, restrict fluids as needed. In hemophilia A: DDAVP releases vWF/factor VIII stores — tachyphylaxis after repeated dosing.",
    "category": "Pharmacology_Systems",
    "subtopic": "Urinary - water-balance receptor targeting",
    "difficulty": "medium",
