    "correctAnswer": "B",
    "rationale": "MOA DETAIL: RENAL PROTECTIVE AGENTS target the pathological pathways driving CKD progression: (1) ACEi/ARBs (lisinopril/losartan) — reduce intraglomerular pressure by dilating the EFFERENT arteriole (angiotensin II preferentially constricts efferent) → decreased glomerular hyperfiltration → reduced proteinuria → slowed nephron loss. Initial GFR dip is expected and acceptable (<30%). (2) SGLT2 INHIBITORS (empagliflozin, dapagliflozin) — block sodium-glucose cotransport in PCT → restore tubuloglomerular feedback → afferent arteriole constriction → reduced glomerular hyperfiltration. Also reduce inflammation and fibrosis. DAPA-CKD and EMPA-KIDNEY showed CKD benefits independent of diabetes. (3) FINERENONE (non-steroidal MRA) — blocks mineralocorticoid receptor-mediated inflammation and fibrosis in the kidney.\n\nKEY MEDICATIONS: lisinopril, losartan, empagliflozin, dapagliflozin, finerenone\n\nCLINICAL APPLICATION: Within Urinary, this scenario is best explained by nephron-hemodynamic pathway modulation for risk reduction.",
    "explanationA": "COX inhibition (NSAIDs) actually REDUCES renal blood flow by inhibiting prostaglandin-mediated afferent arteriolar dilation — HARMFUL in CKD.",
    "explanationB": "Correct. Renal protection targets glomerular hemodynamics (reducing hyperfiltration) and inflammation/fibrosis. ACEi/ARBs dilate the efferent arteriole; SGLT2i restore tubuloglomerular feedback at the afferent arteriole — complementary mechanisms that together provide superior nephroprotection.",
    "explanationC": "DNA gyrase inhibition treats UTIs but does not provide renal protection.",
    "explanationD": "NMJ agonism is irrelevant to renal hemodynamics.",
