    "rationale": "MOA DETAIL: IRON SUPPLEMENTATION replaces depleted iron stores essential for hemoglobin synthesis. Iron is incorporated into protoporphyrin IX to form HEME, which combines with globin chains → functional hemoglobin. (1) ORAL IRON (ferrous sulfate: 65mg elemental Fe per 325mg tab) — absorbed in the duodenum via DMT1 (divalent metal transporter 1); absorption enhanced by ascorbic acid (vitamin C), reduced by PPIs, calcium, and food. Ferrous (Fe2+) forms are better absorbed than ferric (Fe3+). (2) IV IRON (iron sucrose, ferric carboxymaltose) — bypasses GI absorption, used when oral iron fails/not tolerated or rapid repletion needed. IV iron is taken up by macrophages → stored as ferritin → released to transferrin for erythroid use.\n\nKEY MEDICATIONS: ferrous sulfate, ferrous gluconate, iron sucrose, ferric carboxymaltose\n\nCLINICAL APPLICATION: Within Hematology, this scenario is best explained by route-dependent restoration of iron substrate availability.",
