    "explanationB": "Correct. Dual antiplatelet therapy (DAPT: aspirin + P2Y12 inhibitor) blocks two synergistic platelet activation pathways — TXA2 and ADP. This explains why DAPT is standard after ACS/PCI: blocking one pathway alone allows the other to drive continued platelet activation.",
    "explanationC": "DNA gyrase inhibition is a bacterial mechanism unrelated to platelet pharmacology.",
    "explanationD": "NMJ nicotinic agonism has no role in platelet function.",
    "examTip": "Clopidogrel: CYP2C19 poor metabolizers have reduced efficacy — consider pharmacogenomic testing or use ticagrelor/prasugrel instead. DAPT duration post-PCI: 6-12 months (depends on stent type and bleeding risk). Aspirin + P2Y12 inhibitor bleeding risk: hold 5-7 days before elective surgery. Ticagrelor: dyspnea, bradycardia (unique side effects due to adenosine effects).",
