    "rationale": "MOA DETAIL: BETA-LACTAM ANTIBIOTICS (penicillins, cephalosporins, carbapenems) share a common MOA: they inhibit transpeptidase enzymes (penicillin-binding proteins, PBPs) that catalyze the final cross-linking step in bacterial cell wall (peptidoglycan) synthesis. Without cross-linked peptidoglycan, the cell wall weakens → osmotic lysis → bactericidal effect. The BETA-LACTAM RING is the pharmacophore — it mimics the D-Ala-D-Ala terminus of peptidoglycan precursors, forming a covalent bond with PBP active sites. Resistance mechanism: beta-lactamase enzymes hydrolyze the beta-lactam ring → overcome with beta-lactamase inhibitors (clavulanate, tazobactam, avibactam).\n\nKEY MEDICATIONS: amoxicillin, ampicillin, cephalexin, ceftriaxone, meropenem\n\nCLINICAL APPLICATION: Within Immunology, this scenario is best explained by structural assembly blockade causing microbe viability collapse.",
