    "rationale": "MOA DETAIL: IMMUNOSUPPRESSANTS target different immune cell pathways: (1) METHOTREXATE — inhibits dihydrofolate reductase (DHFR) → blocks folate metabolism → reduces purine/pyrimidine synthesis → suppresses rapidly dividing immune cells. At low doses (rheumatologic), also has anti-inflammatory effects via adenosine release. (2) MYCOPHENOLATE — inhibits inosine monophosphate dehydrogenase (IMPDH) → blocks de novo purine synthesis → selectively suppresses T and B lymphocytes (which depend on de novo pathway). (3) CALCINEURIN INHIBITORS (cyclosporine, tacrolimus) — bind immunophilins (cyclophilin/FKBP12) → inhibit calcineurin phosphatase → block IL-2 transcription → prevent T-cell activation. (4) RITUXIMAB — anti-CD20 monoclonal antibody → depletes B cells.\n\nKEY MEDICATIONS: methotrexate, mycophenolate, cyclosporine, tacrolimus, rituximab\n\nCLINICAL APPLICATION: Within Immunology, this scenario is best explained by precision cytokine/receptor pathway modulation in immune disease.",
    "explanationA": "COX inhibition provides anti-inflammatory effect but not the profound immunosuppression needed for transplant rejection or severe autoimmune disease.",
    "explanationB": "Correct. Each immunosuppressant targets a distinct molecular pathway: folate metabolism (methotrexate), purine synthesis (mycophenolate), calcineurin/IL-2 signaling (cyclosporine/tacrolimus), or B-cell depletion (rituximab). This mechanistic diversity allows combination therapy with reduced toxicity of each agent.",
    "explanationC": "DNA gyrase inhibition targets bacteria, not immune cells.",
    "explanationD": "NMJ agonism is irrelevant to immune cell modulation.",
    "examTip": "Methotrexate: supplement with folic acid (reduces mucositis, myelosuppression). Hepatotoxicity, pneumonitis (monitoring: CBC, LFTs, creatinine). Mycophenolate: GI side effects, teratogenic. Calcineurin inhibitors: nephrotoxicity (both), hypertension, diabetes. Cyclosporine: gingival hyperplasia, hirsutism. Tacrolimus: more potent, fewer cosmetic effects. Therapeutic drug monitoring required for both.",
