    "rationale": "MOA DETAIL: ENDOMETRIAL SUPPRESSION is used for endometriosis, adenomyosis, and dysfunctional uterine bleeding: (1) PROGESTINS (norethindrone continuous, levonorgestrel IUD) — directly suppress endometrial proliferation via progesterone receptor activation → endometrial atrophy + decidualization. (2) GnRH AGONISTS (leuprolide) — initially stimulate then DESENSITIZE GnRH receptors (continuous vs pulsatile paradox) → downregulate FSH/LH → hypoestrogenic state ('medical menopause'). (3) GnRH ANTAGONISTS (elagolix) — directly block GnRH receptors → dose-dependent suppression of FSH/LH without initial flare. Both create a hypoestrogenic environment that starves estrogen-dependent endometrial tissue.\n\nKEY MEDICATIONS: medroxyprogesterone, norethindrone, levonorgestrel IUD, GnRH agonists (leuprolide), GnRH antagonists (elagolix)\n\nCLINICAL APPLICATION: Within Women's Health, this scenario is best explained by local endometrial transformation reducing proliferative response.",
