    "explanationB": "Correct. Endometrial suppression works through either direct progesterone receptor activation (endometrial atrophy) or HPG axis shutdown (GnRH modulation creating medical menopause). The GnRH agonist initial 'flare' vs antagonist's immediate suppression is a key mechanistic distinction.",
    "explanationC": "DNA gyrase inhibition is irrelevant to endometrial biology.",
    "explanationD": "NMJ agonism does not affect endometrial tissue.",
    "examTip": "GnRH agonist flare: do NOT start in luteal phase (may stimulate ovulation). Add-back therapy (low-dose estrogen/progestin) after 3-6 months to prevent bone loss and vasomotor symptoms during long-term use. Elagolix: liver toxicity monitoring, dose-dependent estrogen suppression allows some residual estrogen (less severe than leuprolide). Levonorgestrel IUD: excellent first-line for heavy menstrual bleeding.",
