    "rationale": "MOA DETAIL: ANTIDOTES for drug overdose act as competitive antagonists: (1) NALOXONE (Narcan) — competitive μ-opioid receptor antagonist → displaces opioids from receptors → IMMEDIATELY reverses respiratory depression, sedation, miosis. Short half-life (30-90 min) → may need repeated dosing for long-acting opioids (methadone, fentanyl patches). Available: IV, IM, intranasal, auto-injector. (2) NALTREXONE — long-acting oral μ-antagonist for opioid use disorder/alcohol use disorder maintenance (blocks reward pathway). (3) FLUMAZENIL — competitive GABA-A benzodiazepine binding site antagonist → reverses BZD sedation. SHORT half-life — risk of re-sedation. Rarely used due to seizure risk in chronic BZD users or mixed overdose.\n\nKEY MEDICATIONS: naloxone, naltrexone, nalmefene, flumazenil\n\nCLINICAL APPLICATION: Within Pain Management, this scenario is best explained by competitive receptor antagonism with duration-mismatch implications.",
