    "explanationB": "Correct. Dual serotonin/norepinephrine reuptake inhibition enhances the descending pain modulatory system from PAG/RVM to the spinal dorsal horn. This mechanism explains why antidepressants with NE activity (SNRIs, TCAs) are effective analgesics while SSRIs (serotonin only) are not.",
    "explanationC": "DNA gyrase inhibition is irrelevant to pain modulation.",
    "explanationD": "NMJ agonism causes muscle contraction, not pain inhibition.",
    "examTip": "Duloxetine: FDA-approved for diabetic neuropathy, fibromyalgia, chronic musculoskeletal pain, MDD, GAD. Amitriptyline: most evidence for neuropathic pain but anticholinergic burden limits use in elderly. Nortriptyline: less anticholinergic than amitriptyline. Avoid TCAs in cardiac disease (sodium channel blockade → arrhythmia risk). Start low, titrate slowly.",
