    "correctAnswer": "B",
    "rationale": "MOA DETAIL: OPIOIDS act on mu (μ), kappa (κ), and delta (δ) opioid receptors — G protein-coupled receptors that modulate pain signaling: MU (μ) AGONISM (primary analgesic target): → Gi protein activation → (1) inhibits adenylyl cyclase → decreased cAMP, (2) opens K+ channels → neuronal hyperpolarization, (3) closes voltage-gated Ca2+ channels → reduced neurotransmitter release → ANALGESIA. Also causes euphoria, respiratory depression, constipation, and miosis. PARTIAL AGONISTS (buprenorphine) — bind μ receptor with high affinity but lower intrinsic activity → ceiling effect on respiratory depression → safer profile. ANTAGONISTS (naloxone, naltrexone) — compete for μ receptor without activation → reverse all opioid effects.\n\nKEY MEDICATIONS: morphine, oxycodone, hydromorphone, fentanyl, methadone, buprenorphine, naloxone, naltrexone\n\nCLINICAL APPLICATION: Within Pain Management, this scenario is best explained by mu-receptor signaling with intrinsic-activity-dependent safety profile.",
    "explanationA": "COX inhibition is the mechanism of NSAIDs, a different class of analgesics that work peripherally through prostaglandin inhibition rather than central opioid receptor binding.",
    "explanationB": "Correct. Opioid pharmacodynamics centers on μ receptor-mediated Gi signaling: decreased cAMP, K+ channel opening, Ca2+ channel closing → reduced nociceptive transmission. Understanding partial agonism (buprenorphine's ceiling effect) and competitive antagonism (naloxone) directly impacts safe prescribing and overdose management.",
    "explanationC": "DNA gyrase inhibition is irrelevant to pain signaling.",
    "explanationD": "NMJ agonism affects motor function, not nociceptive transmission.",
    "examTip": "Morphine milligram equivalents (MME): monitor total daily MME for overdose risk (>50 MME = increased risk, >90 MME = high risk). Naloxone: IM/IV/IN duration 30-90 min (may need re-dosing for long-acting opioids). Methadone: QT prolongation, complex pharmacokinetics (long half-life, incomplete cross-tolerance). Buprenorphine: for OUD — ceiling effect on respiratory depression makes it safer; requires X-waiver historically (now removed).",
