    "rationale": "MOA DETAIL: NSAIDs inhibit cyclooxygenase (COX) enzymes, blocking arachidonic acid conversion to prostaglandins: (1) NON-SELECTIVE NSAIDs (ibuprofen, naproxen, ketorolac) — inhibit both COX-1 (constitutive: gastric mucosal protection, platelet TXA2, renal blood flow) and COX-2 (inducible: inflammation, pain, fever). (2) COX-2 SELECTIVE (celecoxib) — spares COX-1 → reduced GI ulceration but INCREASED cardiovascular risk (COX-2 produces endothelial prostacyclin, a vasodilator and antiplatelet agent; selective inhibition tips the balance toward thrombosis). Pain relief: reduced prostaglandin E2 (PGE2) → decreased nociceptor sensitization peripherally + reduced central sensitization (spinal COX-2).\n\nKEY MEDICATIONS: ibuprofen, naproxen, celecoxib, ketorolac, diclofenac\n\nCLINICAL APPLICATION: Within Pain Management, this scenario is best explained by cyclooxygenase-mediated prostaglandin pathway reduction.",
    "explanationA": "The correct answer IS about COX inhibition — this directly matches the prostaglandin-mediated inflammatory pain control mechanism.",
    "explanationB": "Correct. NSAID analgesia comes from COX inhibition reducing prostaglandin-mediated peripheral and central nociceptor sensitization. The COX-1 vs COX-2 selectivity determines the side effect profile: GI risk (COX-1) vs cardiovascular risk (COX-2). This mechanistic understanding guides agent selection.",
    "explanationC": "DNA gyrase inhibition is an antibacterial mechanism, not analgesic.",
    "explanationD": "NMJ agonism is irrelevant to inflammatory pain mediator control.",
    "examTip": "Ketorolac: most potent parenteral NSAID, limit to 5 days (GI/renal toxicity). Celecoxib: BLACK BOX for CV events — avoid post-CABG. All NSAIDs: renal toxicity (reduce afferent arteriolar dilation), GI bleeding, hypertension. Avoid in CKD, HF, third trimester pregnancy (premature ductus arteriosus closure). Naproxen: least cardiovascular risk among NSAIDs.",
